<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
The generic name is derived from the Chinese Pinyin 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘cóng">'cong</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="lín’">lin'</normalizedToken>
, meaning 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘forest’">'forest'</normalizedToken>
, in reference to habitat of the new genus. Gender is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
This genus is diagnosed by its complexly routed copulatory ducts and the extended posterior end of the epigynal fig, not found in any other Southeast Asian erigonines (Fig. 24
<normalizedToken originalValue="B–C">B-C</normalizedToken>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Small sized 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Erigoninae">Erigoninae</taxonomicName>
. Carapace unmodified. Chelicerae with 5 promarginal teeth, and 4 retromarginal teeth. Chaetotaxy: tibial spine formula: 1-1-1-1. TmI unknown, TmIV unkown. Abdomen tanned, with dark green patches on the ventral side. Male unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<pageBreakToken pageId="11" pageNumber="12" start="start">Epigyne</pageBreakToken>
: ventral fig round and hunched, with an extension at the posterior end (Fig. 24A); the dorsal fig much shorter than the ventral fig, with curved posterior rim (Fig. 24C). The copulatory ducts long and twisted, and the route difficult to discern (Fig. 24C); no apparent spermathecae present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
